I want to build a deliberately minimal, working version of the Ticketmaster system 
from this design (https://www.hellointerview.com/learn/system-design/problem-breakdowns/ticketmaster),
NOT the full staff-level distributed design — just enough microservices to demonstrate 
the core booking flow with no double-booking, deployable via CI/CD to k3s, testable 
locally first on Rancher Desktop.

GOALS
- Functional requirements only: view events, search events, book tickets (no double booking).
- Skip: virtual waiting queue, Elasticsearch, CDC pipelines, SSE seat updates, dynamic pricing,
  payment gateway integration beyond a mocked/stubbed payment step. These are explicitly 
  out of scope — note them as "below the line" in the README but do not build them.
- Prioritize correctness of the booking concurrency logic (the interesting part of this 
  problem) over breadth of services.

TECH STACK
- Language: Go (use the standard library net/http + a lightweight router like chi, 
  not a heavy framework; pgx or database/sql for Postgres access)
- Container registry: GitHub Container Registry (ghcr.io), images named 
  ghcr.io/<owner>/<repo>/event-service and ghcr.io/<owner>/<repo>/booking-service
- GitHub Actions auth to GHCR via GITHUB_TOKEN (no separate PAT needed for push)

ARCHITECTURE (keep this minimal — do not add components beyond this list unless I ask)
- event-service: view + search events (single Postgres-backed REST service; use Postgres 
  full-text search via tsvector/GIN index for search — NOT Elasticsearch)
- booking-service: reserve + confirm bookings, owns the no-double-booking guarantee using
  the "status + expiration time" pattern (ticket states: available / reserved / booked) 
  with a short transactional check-and-set — no Redis distributed lock, no cron sweep job, 
  unless I explicitly ask to add that later as a v2
- single shared Postgres database for both services (per the article's own reasoning: 
  tightly coupled data, ACID needs, no real benefit to splitting databases here)
- a thin API gateway or ingress route (k3s Traefik ingress is fine — do not stand up a 
  separate API gateway service/pod just for this)
- no message queue, no cache layer, no service mesh — add these only if profiling shows 
  an actual need, not preemptively

EXPLICIT NON-GOALS / OVER-ENGINEERING GUARDRAILS
- Do not introduce Kafka, Elasticsearch, Redis, a service mesh, or extra microservices 
  beyond event-service and booking-service unless I ask.
- Do not split into more than 2 databases.
- Do not add Helm if plain k8s manifests (or kustomize at most) will do for this scale.
- Favor the simplest correct solution for double-booking (DB transaction with optimistic 
  check on ticket status), not the Redis-lock "great solution" — that's a valid v2 
  enhancement, not a v1 requirement.
- Justify any component you add in one sentence: what breaks without it.
- Avoid premature abstraction in Go — no interfaces or layers (repository/service/handler 
  splits) beyond what's needed for the test suite to mock the DB; flat package structure 
  over deeply nested ones.

DELIVERABLES
1. Two small Go services (event-service, booking-service) with clear REST APIs matching 
   the article's endpoints (GET /events/:id, GET /events/search, POST /bookings), each 
   as its own Go module with its own go.mod.
2. Postgres schema/migrations for Event, Venue, Performer, Ticket, Booking entities 
   (plain SQL migration files, use golang-migrate or similar — nothing heavier).
3. Dockerfiles for each service: multi-stage builds producing a static binary on a 
   distroless or scratch final image.
4. Plain Kubernetes manifests (Deployment, Service, Ingress, ConfigMap/Secret for DB conn) 
   organized per-service, designed to run identically on Rancher Desktop's local k3s and 
   a real k3s cluster — no environment-specific hacks. Image pull from ghcr.io requires 
   an imagePullSecret if the package is private — include instructions for creating it.
5. A docker-compose.yml for fast local iteration without k8s (Postgres + both services), 
   but the actual deployment target is k3s manifests, not compose.
6. A GitHub Actions CI/CD pipeline (.github/workflows) that: runs go test ./... (including 
   the booking race condition test), builds and pushes both images to GHCR tagged with 
   git SHA + latest on merge to main, then deploys to the k3s cluster (assume kubeconfig 
   is available as a GitHub secret, e.g. via kubectl apply). Keep the pipeline to as few 
   jobs/steps as needed — no unnecessary stages, no matrix builds unless I ask.
7. A short README covering: how to run locally on Rancher Desktop (kubectl apply against 
   the local k3s context, including the GHCR pull secret setup), how the no-double-booking 
   guarantee works, and what's explicitly out of scope and why.

Include a Go test that spins up concurrent goroutines attempting to book the same ticket 
to prove only one succeeds — this is the one piece of test coverage that actually matters 
for this exercise.

Ask me clarifying questions about repo structure (monorepo with two Go modules vs two 
separate repos) and whether GHCR packages should be public or private before you start 
generating code.